<mxPoint x="8" y="-7" as="offset" /> </mxGeometry> </mxCell> <mxCell id="isoya6EYH9mRprQzXudy-29" value="<font style=""><span style="font-size: 24px;">Guidance</span><br><br><ul><li><font style=""><font style="font-size: 18px;">The user token is used by UI services to authorise access to features within them.</font></font></li><li><font style=""><font style="font-size: 18px;">Service-to-service calls (including UI to API calls) should use a client token.</font></font></li><li><font style=""><font style="font-size: 18px;">Transactions initiated by users should use a client token which has the username set within it, to cater for accurate auditing.</font></font></li><li><font style=""><font style="font-size: 18px;">Transactions with no users involved (e.g. events, cronjobs) should use a client token with no username set within it.</font></font></li><li><font style=""><font style="font-size: 18px;">Client tokens can be requested with the username by adding <i>?username=&lt;username&gt;</i>&nbsp;to the client credentials token endpoint.</font></font></li><li><font style=""><font style="font-size: 18px;">Beware if caching client tokens which which contain usernames - these should only be cached or used for this specific user.</font></font></li><li><font style=""><font style="font-size: 18px;">Client tokens which are without a username may be cached and re-used in multiple calls for similar endpoints.</font></font></li><li><font style=""><font style="font-size: 18px;">There are exceptions to this guidance - some endpoints require the user token e.g. Prison API /api/user/me, /api/user/me/caseloads - these should be called with the user token.</font></font></li></ul><div><font style="font-size: 24px;">Why?</font></div><div><span style="font-size: 18px;"><br></span></div><div><ul><li><span style="font-size: 18px;">We are all seeing a proliferation of roles and there is a growing administrative burden in setting these <i>per user</i>.</span></li><li><span style="font-size: 18px;">Using client tokens for service to service API calls will significantly simplify the administration of user roles.</span></li><li><span style="font-size: 18px;">Common API endpoints need only set a role which allows specific clients to call them - rather than a range of user roles.</span></li></ul></div></font>"
